The Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament has rejected, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the draft cancellation of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Yulia Tymoshenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected in second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing sentences for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former prime minister currently imprisoned.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding an a priori unfavorable agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is due to decide on the convict’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko describes the verdict as political revenge of the regime and has provoked a process of suspicion of court bias also in the West.
The bill to repeal paragraph 365 of the Criminal Law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
