The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendules that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 was chairman of the Board of Supervisors of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then shadowed the company's founder - it was on Watson's ideas that the company's identity and culture so far rested.
