How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered tours mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination to the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
The travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but you had to keep the queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
Even after that, it was not yet won.
The deal for currencies that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought themselves and this custom lasts until now.
The Czech travel industry has undergone a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their maximum,the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in Western neighboring countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations were making the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or pension.
The typical feature of a trip from the Czech Republic at this time was to bring with you your own food canned, sausages, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists after decades to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased which caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to the growing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to prepare tours with air charter connections that, thanks to contracts, have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
By the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except for the U.S., which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including the attached charges.
