21st House in Vienna
The flag that moved
by Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with highs, lows and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruins.
It is now re-opened as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, its clear shapes, its glass hangars, its vivid and bold appearances and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels Universal Exhibition is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight and suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is still considered to be an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian Universal Exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW home and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Garden of Switzerland at the Southern Vienna Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and increasingly degraded.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st Century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a hit of luck in all respects.
The new start was led by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career, among other things in her youth as an art skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she carried out especially well the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments, she obtained public and private sponsorship and established its exploitation.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name were exhibited there, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht’s secession and had won the contest, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was “an extremely important place” where he had seen “practically every weekend” the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and by its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was “an energy gap,” Krischanitz says.
The window profiles of the glass façades were changed, insulating glass reinforced in fiberglass was placed and the roof replaced with a special safety glass.
Thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements made room for the new exploitation, a tinted light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leading to the entrance - it's almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The exterior doors of origin have remained, the house is painted in a protection shade against rust of red-brown color.
And the cinema room is even exactly the same as it was before.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for the monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that were good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also pleased the office of protection monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and lightweight.
It would have been difficult with the Flag, “which came from Brussels,” Krischanitz recently said, a typical story of “Drop-in-the-City.”
Such an architecture is “always in the wrong place” and nevertheless wants to “wake up a good conscience.”
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Jardin Suisse stands precisely the newly planned "central station district", with offices and apartments.
And another chance may happen: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, as the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
