Peter Englund’s new book, titled “The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War,” begins with a long list of characters that touch your heart.
A tip to get started: scratch this page carefully and make it your page tag.
In this novel narrative by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a tag during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mist of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which delivers the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as “an anti-historic work.”
It has a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is hardly any ambassador or discussion about strategies and equipment.
It’s not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a “book describing what it might look like.”
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the experiences in wartime of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulances and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war. Some will lose members, get mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives vacillate here like the candles of a church: while some turn off, new ones are lit up.
Peter Englund’s book differs from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that the First World War was merely the terrible war of the tranches on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully describes other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under the hills; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an untouchable problem.
This book is exciting from the first page.
War has invaded the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you’re a home mother, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, nor even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “The lack of facts has been aggravated by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young seamen in the German offshore fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be frightening or exciting, but are most preserved through the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most address deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
Telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on replacement food in Germany.
He describes “meat made from cooked rice crushed into sheep fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made from dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe socks.”
He claims that “837 permitted substitute meats are registered in sausage production.
Some stories talk about honor and courage.
One American acknowledges his own urge for savagery and says about war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant for, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, cigarette and whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper or bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a vernis is synonymous with civilization, and that there's no barbar behind your squeezed and nailed shirt.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is at great risk of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention to it.
“When one is resigned to sacrifice, one hopes to have a public,” he wrote.
Unfortunately, this is rather comparable to “a convicted man strangled in secret.”
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
“Conflict is increasingly becoming a history of economic competition,” writes Peter Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captures the arrival of what he calls “a new species within the early-century bestiary: the well-articulated and ideologically convinced mass killer, in well-cut clothes, who performs his slaughter while sitting behind a counter.”
People act unexpectedly; there are as many basic behaviors as heroism.
Peter Englund talks about soldiers who tried at all costs to catch a venereal disease in prostitutes in order to avoid front service.
"The most grotesque expression is found in the trade of pus due to gonorrhea, which soldiers buy and spread on the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he writes.
