Walls Have Eyes: Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy expressing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to being caught up in a murderous madness in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, faced his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being in cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
It is easy to connect to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t that difficult to find them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by DEMOS’ think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy – the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett’s team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and colleagues were able to question 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way to do research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Thought groups, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study all the topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through “I like”, walled publications, and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, the “data supernova” is generating an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to conduct investigations into people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You should have gone to the party, but they would never have allowed you in," says Jamie Bartlett.
“Facebook avoids all of this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken feats were much more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” says Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site’s data team studied statistics on love situation and Valentine’s Day, the 2010 midterm election participation rate, and a national happiness index (thanks to the only information available – digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information otherwise than by going through the Internet, there’s a whole other thing about online.
“I don’t think a lot of users have ever thought about a researcher studying their profile,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students’ Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things,” says Neil Selwyn.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn thinks a notebook and pen is still the best tools one can use.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he said.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and the social, it's not in front of a computer."
