While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that major copies have disappeared in transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly upgraded, is the basis for the 68-minute film titled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be aired in cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems here surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions – between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism reappeared, where he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him elbows to get him to speed up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous assessments of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then follows them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a company:
“Over all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That is what I discovered.
Steve Jobs continues to give details about his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed about how costs were recorded—often starting with a “standard cost” estimated in the nose, then adjusted with a “variation”—he developed an automated factory that guaranteed accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour to the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack phone networks and make free long-distance phone calls.
The device has been the subject of many writings in advance, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you yelled at the public phone and it happened to you a minute later at the public phone next door,” Jobs said laughing.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn’t know much, but we were able to invent a small thing that could control big things.It was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful tour that he and Wozniak have developed: he called the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to talk to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go out laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
About his love for technology (and Bill Hewlett’s demeanor):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searched for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gave him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated.”
Steve Jobs later became one of HP employees to visit the company's research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for that machine.
Improvisation of Innovation:
In the interview, Steve Jobs talked about the invention of new products.
At the beginning of his career, as he settles to sell a few printed circuit cards, a customer asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he encountered in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember big quarrels... I was screaming at them saying that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I got enough, I went out and went to see a designer.”
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and which proved incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are falling:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had predicted how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, you’re making a better copier or a better printer, and then?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these kinds of people] end up leading and product-specialized personnel are put aside from decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotted by people who cannot imagine designing a good product over a bad product – the required manual work.
That’s what happened with Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
Xerox could have been the Microsoft of the 1990s.
They brought defeat to victory.
Innovation as an Art Form:
“A lot of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
Some things you can’t do, the electrons can, the glass, the robots, the factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste.It’s about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you’re creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed of stealing great ideas.
The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it were for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas Dinner with Health Law Opponents as Court Meet
On the day the Supreme Court meets behind closed doors to examine the issue of political discord, namely whether opposition to President Obama’s health law will be heard, two of its judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were noticed at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will defend the case before the Supreme Court.
The event took place last Thursday, when the nine judges met for a conference to discuss petitions for review.
One of the cases involved a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the ambitious health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a landmark for conservative activists nationwide.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, in fact, a monumental argument of 5:30 is expected next March, and the outcome will likely favor the destabilization of the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing at the time the court decision will be made.
The lawyer who will stand in court and argue on the rejection of the law will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. General Applicant during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was one of two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another promoter was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the dispute.
The dinner took place at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court conference on the case.
Among them was Mitch McConnell, a top Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health law.
The guests starred at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: the two judges have been present at the events of the Federalist Society for years.
Nothing goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would argue by the Canon 4C code, which stipulates: “A judge may attend fundraising from law-related and other organizations even though the judge may not be a speaker, an honorary guest, or appearing on the agenda of such an event.”
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas near two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
"This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the Court respects the same rules applicable to all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were drinking and dining and at a gala fundraising with lawyers who have cases in court."
Their presence and participation in the fundraising of this event disproves any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little respect for critics claiming that they too easily mix court affairs with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’s wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
Furthermore, Conservatives argue that it is Judge Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was the general applicant of the Obama administration when the first objections to the law were raised at the first-instance court level.
Her critics pressured Kagan to refuse to hear the case, saying she had invested too much in defending the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would do so.
Boeing orders $18 billion for aircraft
Emirates airline ordered 50 Boeing 777, two-corridor aircraft, with the possibility to purchase 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Oman Air, a market estimated at more than $1 billion.
There is nothing extraordinary about a company receiving an order covering 50 of its products.
It is, on the other hand, an affair when the company in question is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing and the amount of these 50 aircraft reaches the record sum of $18 billion.
Equally incredible is who Boeing received this order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a forecast released on Monday, the Chicago airline estimates that the Middle East airlines will need 2,520 aircraft worth a total of $450 billion over the next 20 years.
During the weekend, Boeing announced the most expensive commercial aircraft order in its history - 50 Boeing 777 bi-corridor.
It is the Emirates airline based in Dubai that passed this pharaonic order.
Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Air Show that the airline is also likely to purchase 20 more aircraft, raising the total order amount to $26 billion.
On the other hand, Boeing said on Monday that Oman Air has ordered six Boeing 787-8, nicknamed the Dreamliners, a model that features significant fuel savings and comfort for passengers.
The amount of these six devices amounts to more than a billion dollars.
“This is clearly very positive for Boeing,” said Neal Dihora, an analyst at Morningstar.
“These customers in particular have immense value.”
In the Middle East, oil-producing countries own many of their airlines.
So not only do they have the means to pay for these planes, but a rise in fuel price – usually detrimental to airlines because it represents their highest expenses – would not be so detrimental to them as the country would make money with rising oil prices.
This is an important point because these companies will be less likely than others to cancel or postpone their aircraft orders when oil prices rise, Dihora said.
“They have a natural risk coverage,” he said.
The Emirates order strengthens Boeing’s dominance in the bulk aircraft market and helps to curb the attempt of competitor Airbus to engage with its A350 aircraft.
Boeing’s victory at the aeronautics show comes four months after Airbus announced it would postpone the debut of the larger version of the A350, which directly rivals the Boeing 777-300ER.
Airbus is postponing its debut to increase its push after its customers demand to increase its loading capacity and range.
Boeing’s shares rose by 1.5% to $67.94.
Mexican president's sister defeated in Michoacán elections
Luisa Maria Calderon says drug traffickers helped her PRI opponent Fausto Vallejo in the race for governor.
President Felipe Calderon's sister appears to have lost her attempt to gain access to the Michoacán governor's post during violent elections, and she said on Monday that drug traffickers favoured one of her opponents.
Early results indicated that Fausto Vallejo of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was at the forefront of the race for governor of this western state.
“The intervention of organized crime during the entire voting process and especially yesterday is an alarming fact, not only for Michoacán but for the whole country,” said Luisa Maria Calderon in an interview on Monday after the election.
“They threatened our candidates, our electoral agents... They seized the polling stations, installed road barricades... and forced people to vote” for the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seventy years until losing the presidency in 2000.
But he organizes his return, and a victory in the Michoacán is an important step in this effort.
The PRI hopes to win the presidential election in July.
Vallejo appears to have only slightly stand out from Calderon, who was at the top of the polls before the election day.
Calderon, a candidate from his brother’s Conservative Party, the National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, the left-wing candidate of the Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, who currently holds the positions of governor, came third, a painful defeat ahead of the 2012 presidential election for this divided and unhappy left.
Aureoles also refused to acknowledge the first results.
Vallejo, a former mayor of Morelia, the state’s capital, denied any connection with drug traffickers and strongly advised other candidates to accept the results.
Michoacán has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in the trafficking of marijuana, heroin and methamphetamine.
It is the home state of President Calderon, and he chose Michoacán to launch a military offensive against traffickers in December 2006.
However, the violence has persisted.
A week before the election a PAN mayor was assassinated while campaigning for Luisa Maria Calderon, and many candidates resigned locally from the campaign out of fear.
However, for the PRI, as corrupt as the Michoacán elections seem, a victory will help the party in its momentum.
The man expected to represent the PRI in the presidential race, Enrique Pena Nieto, congratulated Vallejo from Washington and said, “I think this victory is very encouraging for next year.”
BASD Urges Asia to Help Eurozone
The Asian Development Bank has called on India and China to prepare to help the euro zone out of the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term downturn that would hinder the development of the Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, managing director of the Manila-based BASD, said the world’s two fastest-growing economic powers should “do everything in their power” to accelerate the recovery of the monetary zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He advised the BRICs (Brazil, Russia, India, China) not to look at Europe’s difficulties with an “indifferent eye” and noted that Asian financial support alongside European leaders and resources would prevent a long-term collapse of the global economy.
“We are all in this crisis.”
"Therefore, anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times during an interview during the World Economic Forum in Bombay.
“Asia can be protected to some extent, but it is not safe.”
“So if China and India can help, let nothing stop them.”
In recent months, the eurozone has been severely shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of Italian loans has dangerously climbed and the Prime Ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The flourishing sovereign debt crisis in Europe has sparked fears that the global economy will go into recession, and has prompted major emerging economies to come together to help the euro area find a solution.
Nag predicted that the IMF would forward any Asian aid, but he also said that this bilateral assistance – such as buying bonds from the U.S. financial rescue fund, the European Financial Stability Fund – would offer greater negotiating power to Europe’s Asian partners.
India's Minister of Commerce and Industry, Anand Sharma, said India "will do everything it can" to help the eurozone as its own economy is now suffering from a decline in exports and a tightening of foreign capital arrivals.
“No one wants the eurozone to remain unstable and agitated,” he said.
“We have monumental challenges to face and we need to maintain a high level of growth.”
"This is not a choice, it is an imperative, because where would we find work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help the wealthy Europeans as they face their own major economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said it would be politically very difficult to accept aid to Europe for 1.2 billion Indians, of whom at least 800,000 live on $2 a day or less.
"One day they will find out that the Greeks retire at 50 and go on holiday in the sun and they will have a hard time swallowing it," he said.
Lee Howell, the president of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep many well-paid Greek officials in poorly managed jobs that generate losses, like in the railway sector.
Nag said the eurozone crisis could have “significant repercussions” across Asia.
BASD’s forecasts of 7.5% economic growth in Asia in 2011/2012 now face “loss risks” due to the European threat.
He noted that vulnerable emerging markets needed to "develop rescue plans" to protect themselves from economic turmoil and significant capital leaks.
Pentagon warns of potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta raised pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 or more amount of compression is imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the ministry," Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in what is called seizure would result in 23% cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a large reduction, applied so discreetly, would make most of our ships and construction projects impossible - you can't buy three-quarters of a ship or building - and seriously impair other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We would also be forced to separate ourselves from a number of our civilian personnel and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost have to send civilians on unpaid leave in order to the goal."
“These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparation.”
The reductions would eventually affect combating troops, Panetta continues.
"Al wartime funding of foreign emergency operations accounts is not directly affected by the seizure, war efforts would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in basic budgets," Panetta warned.
“The contracting staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracts and supervision of contracts that support war.”
“The staff managing wages would be reduced, resulting in late payments to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of automatic compressions on the Defense Ministry.
“The consequence of a seizure on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader of military power.”
"We are fiercely opposed to this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement on Monday afternoon when Panetta's letter was published.
"It's not a consequence we can live with, and it's not the one we should impose on ourselves."
"The seizure is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen."
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from cuts, remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible compressions, even though he himself reached the top post of the Pentagon accumulating years of budget expertise at Congress and the White House and knowing that he was facing difficult choices.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a dark picture of what could happen - a military with a shell but no core.
“This is a ship without sailors.”
“It’s a brigade without bullets.”
“It’s a fighter aircraft, with not enough trained pilots.”
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don't have enough trained soldiers capable of carrying out the mission," Panetta said in his preliminary remarks to the Pentagon.
“It’s a depressed force, poorly prepared and unable to deal with potential opponents.”
“In fact, it calls for aggression.”
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how new cuts could “generate significant operational risks: delayed response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits to our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable risk assumed in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could go to the cut, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship, and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Stopping the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is a key step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Discover a Lie
A look at recent headlines shows how ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, turned out to be an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violating campaign funding related to covering an extra-marital relationship.
And then, no one who has lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legionary.
There have been instances where teachers gave test answers to students in order to show themselves well on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
In a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lie to each other three times within the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone needs to acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a company game like, say, charades, where the goal is to scream: "I got you," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research of such projects, notably in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been demystified.
The liars are looking you in the eyes.
They don’t blush, red, or stir up all the time.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A skilled lie detector can discover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I’ve spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about cheating, and it’s clear that cheating detection is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and useful to navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more “self-centered” lies while women say more “other-centered” lies – usually to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called “establishing data benchmarks.”
This helps provide a benchmark for measuring future changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves their feet constantly so as not to cast unfair accusations when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and non-verbal misleading behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, bend toward an exit, change posture significantly, or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated soup of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is finished just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson stumbled away using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Misleading individuals may also use a distant language: “I didn’t have sex with this woman... Mrs. Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of “wood tongue” when answering a difficult question: “Well... to say truth... if I remember goods... to my knowledge.”
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for lying detection, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial pipeline plan will be overturned after late U.S. approval threat
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay the approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico – provoking trade unions’ anger while calming environmentalists – the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is ready to redirect the project to put it back on track.
TransCanada said on Monday night that it will move the projected pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive area of the Nebraska dunes, and is confident that the project will still win its approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference in the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada official Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident that it will eventually obtain approval for a pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the State Department’s announcement last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal permit for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid areas of the Nebraska Dunes and Ogallala Aquifer, vast groundwater springs.
“It’s a real path forward,” Lee Terry, a Nebraska Republican, told Fox News.
The new environmental review commissioned by the State Department would likely have postponed any decision until 2013, after next year’s elections, although officials deny political involvement in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as a State Department decision, and expressed his support for it.
The 2.735 km pipeline would extend from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would transport 700,000 barrels per day from the province of Alberta to the refineries of Texas.
To do this, it would have to go through six countries.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, who have bet on the estimated 20,000 pipeline-related jobs.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to this plan are pushing for a law to force the Sand Hills region and the Ogallala aquifer away, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s ongoing environmental impact study found that the project would have only limited negative environmental impacts, but the energy industry said the Department’s inspector-general ordered a separate investigation of the review process, centered on two issues.
One is that a TransCanada-held lobbyist, Paul Elliott, who was a Hillary Clinton campaign adviser in 2008, would represent a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a company that was hired to conduct the initial study was an inappropriate choice because of its relationship with TransCanada.
