Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez’s management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated high expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in return there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing trillion-dollar losses to the agricultural sector, limited the opportunities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic 31.16 percent drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
