The Court validates the "analogous cut" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has defeated the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Representatives have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogic cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes needed to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to concrete the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was defeated for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, due to the fact that the regulation in the field of radio and television is an attribution reserved by law to the Federal Commission of Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Representatives promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers also decided to debute the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for them.
"I also do not consider that if he did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has as a constitutional mandate the management of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this results in better exploitation of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitalization, which involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, “because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These questions, he stressed, “require the operation of a whole established system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompassing a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the State Executive.”
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded the sphere of competence of Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
Analysis of the possibility of a "vot per vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote per vote" is a reality with regard to this year's election process in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Program of Preliminary Electoral Results (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be remembered that Michoacán did not homologate either its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, while the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process to come into effect and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided by the State Journal Act, arguing that he had some objections.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislative Power and called the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal", as he has no right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to carry out partial and total counting of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no ballot minutes and counting in the file of the ballot is not with the president of the same; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the votes received in all the polling stations of the election may be carried out when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged winner of the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or below one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition that submitted the second of the candidates.
The total counting of the vote may also be carried out if at the end of the joint counting it turns out that the difference between the supposedly winning candidate and the candidate of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party whose candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial counting are excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of Morelia's election, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the total 923 minutes.
