The new government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form the government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed in its majority of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
“The framework is now well drawn,” he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy struggles with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels unbearable.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability has placed the 10-year yield of Italian bonds BTP above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti’s chances of success have been greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He will end his tour of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was about to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
