Quinteto included the country in its tour to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"To go to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited for more than 20 years, but the group assures that it will also be a dream made reality for them to perform in this country.
That’s what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is in the South American wing of its two-decade-long celebration tour and will make its only stop in Central America on Sunday 20.
That day they will perform on the National Stadium, starting at 19:30, alongside the Los Angeles group The X and the national of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcription of which can be found in The Nation on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream made reality.
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once on vacation; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’ll be able to spend a few days there.
So it’s exciting to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the group, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we’re sorry that it took so long for this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we have offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We gave a giant two shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, alongside Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned it, through the people who love surfing.
As you watched the tour, you offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the record.
What is this due to?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, which is why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to play each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have not played for a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us why we loved those songs and we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve achieved?
Yes absolutely .
First, I think none of us had imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and being able to continue making music together is very emotional.
We love each other and we love to make music.
We’re lucky to go to places in the world we’ve always wanted to go to.
Things could not go better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we attended a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with them all and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that is much longer than many groups normally last.
First, I think we are all lucky to be still alive and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and that couldn’t go better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don’t spend too much time on touring because it’s easy to fall into this game of large crowds and people who love your music.
If we don’t forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we have to respect the music and what brought it, without putting in mind the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn’t really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn’t release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There has been a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important thing is the fact that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or see a photo I think of the incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music, football and many other things with him.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that’s why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we’re looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and that must be very distracting.
Why do you always change the words of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He is the one who sings it and I think he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge up, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time and, if that’s relevant now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s a music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney now make the best music than ever.
