He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After achieving the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Unit Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the aim of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their family history of inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic measurements will be applied to all participants (it is sought to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López that this investigation is the result of health professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
“Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, 77 percent in obesity and in the case of girls, 47 percent; in the case of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed,” said the IMSS specialist.
He pointed out that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
He that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heritage, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
Ila even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic changes and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors hand it over in writing to parents, to whom each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to implement to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another reason is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat-to-meat paste corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid crashes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Zone, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of the bitumen pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of cracks.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heaviest molecular weight, called asphaltens, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents a solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes fragile, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he noted, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating effort, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the layer of asphalt, he says, a last layer is laid called a layer of rolling, made of fine stone, that is, of sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the effort, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as they greatly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to get out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes cracks.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first to break is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle load is another important factor for cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement should always be linked to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to be investigated and worked on asphalt, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair the cracks easily and without having to use high temperatures.
