This was the work of Cali's person who identified Alfonso Cano's body
A Cali dactyloscopist has gone into history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4 a Dactyloscopist of the Cali CTI went into history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven dactyloscopists working in the local CTI offices, this week it was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of criminal investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the woods to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much slimmer.
Fingerprints do not lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian lump, ink, a pickup and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of Fingerprint
For a dactyloscopist of Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against “Cano”, is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, with no margin of error, which can be crucial in resolving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, fingerprints support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identities of the captured people.
When captured, many criminals present fake identity cards or lack documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that in one case of theft he had to remove a piece of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had pushed his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in various thefts," he remembers.
Fingerprints can also dismiss or confirm suspects in murder cases.
Recently, a man was found dead, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a parent may be suspected of the crime and indeed a footprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it puts him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint scanner explained that "fingerprints from objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a pickup or tape is used to pick them up.
Fingerprints are subsequently sent to Asif, the declinant database, or the National Civil Register.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," the CTI expert said.
He explained that everything is not as shown in the CSI television program.
As not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch becomes a footprint.
However, it can be used, if the necessary confrontation is made.
