Inclusion of a "golden rule" in the constitution
The government of the great social-democratic/Christian-democratic coalition in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to insert a "golden rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by the rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It is the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision after a council of ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the maximum criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
"If Austria's creditworthiness were to be reduced by a single cranium, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more interest each year," said Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus follows a request from the eurozone summit in Brussels on October 26: the heads of state and government had then demanded that by the end of 2012 the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts be included in the constitution or in a law of equal value.
The arrangement adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", with Germany being the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit will have to decrease annually by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural government deficit of the federal state will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP annually, while regional states and municipalities will have to present budgets at balance.
The objective is to bring the public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
