European champion of wind power, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; according to which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than the French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy constitutes a key competitiveness factor and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Therefore, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power illusory.
A price that a large majority of French refuse to pay, especially since they do not manifest opposition in principle to this energy, polls show it.
