There is a broad consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot welcome all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared both on the left and on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity we are willing to give to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande covers banality, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be payable electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, p.
Restricting immigration undermines growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are at risk of replacing domestic workers, especially low-skilled workers, putting down pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes to domestic workers, exercising for the most part professions in sectors with shortages of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow job offerings.
Positive effects on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrival of immigrants have a positive effect on nationals’ salaries and employment.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows results in an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in long-term real wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among US Nobel prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, accounting for an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will contribute a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of 150,000 euros to the public budgets on average throughout his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points "with the teeth."
The teeth in question, serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
