Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It will supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brightness.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on Tuesday, on the banks of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte together turned the wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1.224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, or the equivalent of all French consumption.
There is also the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site is a victory.
The project was heavily contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
The issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies there.
But it’s at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, which are heavily consuming gas and whose deposits are declining.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way,” Fillon said when inaugurating the pipeline, demonstrating how much the major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number at Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mining fields dating from World War II.
"A hundred had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures have also been taken to protect flora and fauna.
The tube is a long metal snake, weighing as much as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts throughout its length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the Swedish coast, but the project officials abandoned it as the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company establish permanently off their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, pulled by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, a meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it delivers accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
There are 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to this project.
Gazprom holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
Its headquarters is in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their costs, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy shore planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine is a brand book.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
He has a smell of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine booklet as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of launching the new product.
The carnet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (taupe skin), which refers to a lacquered cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of book was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who became the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million units.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 booklets were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, as the notebook attracts both the businessman, student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, now has 100 employees and has had two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has been able to impose her identity.
“We have followed the weather and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own booklet.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand stands on a whole range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of people with disabilities so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Persons with Disabilities begins today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
and discouraging?
“No,” points out Éric Blanchet, general director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress that has been made over the past 15 years is considerable.”
At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.
“H, there is still a lot to be done.”
Unemployed persons with disabilities have many obstacles to access employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that singularly complicate the return to employment, and that "constitute the node of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is about the objective brakes.
There are mentalities that are evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the City indicated that managers surveyed have “a low level of knowledge of disability”, with a “overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a 1987 law.
The last known figures, dated from 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, general director of Afif, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
